aa(lp47
VNow, making drought-tolerant crops is not the easiest thing in the world.
p48
aVAnd the reason for this is water.
p49
aVWater is essential to life on this planet.
p50
aVAll living, actively metabolizing organisms,
p51
aVfrom microbes to you and I,
p52
aVare comprised predominately of water.
p53
aVAll life reactions happen in water.
p54
aVAnd loss of a small amount of water results in death.
p55
aVYou and I are 65 percent water \u2014
p56
aVwe lose one percent of that, we die.
p57
aVBut we can make behavioral changes to avoid that.
p58
aVPlants can't.
p59
aVThey're stuck in the ground.
p60
aVAnd so in the first instance they have a little bit more water than us,
p61
aVabout 95 percent water,
p62
aVand they can lose a little bit more than us,
p63
aVlike 10 to about 70 percent, depending on the species,
p64
aVbut for short periods only.
p65
aa(lp66
VMost of them will either try to resist or avoid water loss.
p67
aVSo extreme examples of resistors can be found in succulents.
p68
aVThey tend to be small, very attractive,
p69
aVbut they hold onto their water at such great cost
p70
aVthat they grow extremely slowly.
p71
aVExamples of avoidance of water loss are found in trees and shrubs.
p72
aVThey send down very deep roots,
p73
aVmine subterranean water supplies
p74
aVand just keep flushing it through them at all times,
p75
aVkeeping themselves hydrated.
p76
aa(lp77
VThe one on the right is called a baobab.
p78
aVIt's also called the upside-down tree,
p79
aVsimply because the proportion of roots to shoots is so great
p80
aVthat it looks like the tree has been planted upside down.
p81
aVAnd of course the roots are required for hydration of that plant.
p82
aa(lp83
VAnd probably the most common strategy of avoidance is found in annuals.
p84
aVAnnuals make up the bulk of our plant food supplies.
p85
aVUp the west coast of my country,
p86
aVfor much of the year you don't see much vegetation growth.
p87
aVBut come the spring rains, you get this:
p88
aVflowering of the desert.
p89
aa(lp90
VThe strategy in annuals,
p91
aVis to grow only in the rainy season.
p92
aVAt the end of that season they produce a seed,
p93
aVwhich is dry, eight to 10 percent water,
p94
aVbut very much alive.
p95
aVAnd anything that is that dry and still alive,
p96
aVwe call desiccation-tolerant.
p97
aa(lp98
VIn the desiccated state,
p99
aVwhat seeds can do is lie in extremes of environment
p100
aVfor prolonged periods of time.
p101
aVThe next time the rainy season comes,
p102
aVthey germinate and grow,
p103
aVand the whole cycle just starts again.
p104
aa(lp105
VIt's widely believed that the evolution of desiccation-tolerant seeds
p106
aVallowed the colonization and the radiation
p107
aVof flowering plants, or angiosperms, onto land.
p108
aa(lp109
VBut back to annuals as our major form of food supplies.
p110
aVWheat, rice and maize form 95 percent of our plant food supplies.
p111
aVAnd it's been a great strategy
p112
aVbecause in a short space of time you can produce a lot of seed.
p113
aVSeeds are energy-rich so there's a lot of food calories,
p114
aVyou can store it in times of plenty for times of famine,
p115
aVbut there's a downside.
p116
aVThe vegetative tissues,
p117
aVthe roots and leaves of annuals,
p118
aVdo not have much
p119
aVby way of inherent resistance, avoidance or tolerance characteristics.
p120
aVThey just don't need them.
p121
aVThey grow in the rainy season
p122
aVand they've got a seed to help them survive the rest of the year.
p123
aa(lp124
VAnd so despite concerted efforts in agriculture
p125
aVto make crops with improved properties
p126
aVof resistance, avoidance and tolerance \u2014
p127
aVparticularly resistance and avoidance
p128
aVbecause we've had good models to understand how those work \u2014
p129
aVwe still get images like this.
p130
aVMaize crop in Africa,
p131
aVtwo weeks without rain
p132
aVand it's dead.
p133
aa(lp134
VThere is a solution:
p135
aVresurrection plants.
p136
aVThese plants can lose 95 percent of their cellular water,
p137
aVremain in a dry, dead-like state for months to years,
p138
aVand give them water,
p139
aVthey green up and start growing again.
p140
aVLike seeds, these are desiccation-tolerant.
p141
aVLike seeds, these can withstand extremes of environmental conditions.
p142
aVAnd this is a really rare phenomenon.
p143
aVThere are only 135 flowering plant species that can do this.
p144
