aa(lp155
VSo I've spent the last 21 years trying to understand how they do this.
p156
aVHow do these plants dry without dying?
p157
aVAnd I work on a variety of different resurrection plants,
p158
aVshown here in the hydrated and dry states,
p159
aVfor a number of reasons.
p160
aa(lp161
VOne of them is that each of these plants serves as a model
p162
aVfor a crop that I'd like to make drought-tolerant.
p163
aa(lp164
VSo on the extreme top left, for example, is a grass,
p165
aVit's called Eragrostis nindensis,
p166
aVit's got a close relative called Eragrostis tef \u2014
p167
aVa lot of you might know it as "teff" \u2014
p168
aVit's a staple food in Ethiopia,
p169
aVit's gluten-free,
p170
aVand it's something we would like to make drought-tolerant.
p171
aa(lp172
VThe other reason for looking at a number of plants,
p173
aVis that, at least initially,
p174
aVI wanted to find out: do they do the same thing?
p175
aVDo they all use the same mechanisms
p176
aVto be able to lose all that water and not die?
p177
aa(lp178
VSo I undertook what we call a systems biology approach
p179
aVin order to get a comprehensive understanding
p180
aVof desiccation tolerance,
p181
aVin which we look at everything
p182
aVfrom the molecular to the whole plant, ecophysiological level.
p183
aa(lp184
VFor example we look at things like
p185
aVchanges in the plant anatomy as they dried out
p186
aVand their ultrastructure.
p187
aVWe look at the transcriptome, which is just a term for a technology
p188
aVin which we look at the genes
p189
aVthat are switched on or off, in response to drying.
p190
aVMost genes will code for proteins, so we look at the proteome.
p191
aVWhat are the proteins made in response to drying?
p192
aVSome proteins would code for enzymes which make metabolites,
p193
aVso we look at the metabolome.
p194
aa(lp195
VNow, this is important because plants are stuck in the ground.
p196
aVThey use what I call a highly tuned chemical arsenal
p197
aVto protect themselves from all the stresses of their environment.
p198
aVSo it's important that we look
p199
aVat the chemical changes involved in drying.
p200
aa(lp201
VAnd at the last study that we do at the molecular level,
p202
aVwe look at the lipidome \u2014
p203
aVthe lipid changes in response to drying.
p204
aVAnd that's also important
p205
aVbecause all biological membranes are made of lipids.
p206
aVThey're held as membranes because they're in water.
p207
aVTake away the water, those membranes fall apart.
p208
aVLipids also act as signals to turn on genes.
p209
aa(lp210
VThen we use physiological and biochemical studies
p211
aVto try and understand the function of the putative protectants
p212
aVthat we've actually discovered in our other studies.
p213
aVAnd then use all of that to try and understand
p214
aVhow the plant copes with its natural environment.
p215
aa(lp216
VI've always had the philosophy that I needed a comprehensive understanding
p217
aVof the mechanisms of desiccation tolerance
p218
aVin order to make a meaningful suggestion for a biotic application.
p219
aa(lp220
VI'm sure some of you are thinking,
p221
aV"By biotic application,
p222
aVdoes she mean she's going to make genetically modified crops?"
p223
aVAnd the answer to that question is:
p224
aVdepends on your definition of genetic modification.
p225
aa(lp226
VAll of the crops that we eat today, wheat, rice and maize,
p227
aVare highly genetically modified from their ancestors,
p228
aVbut we don't consider them GM
p229
aVbecause they're being produced by conventional breeding.
p230
aVIf you mean, am I going to put resurrection plant genes into crops,
p231
aVyour answer is yes.
p232
aa(lp233
VIn the essence of time, we have tried that approach.
p234
aVMore appropriately, some of my collaborators at UCT,
p235
aVJennifer Thomson, Suhail Rafudeen,
p236
aVhave spearheaded that approach
p237
aVand I'm going to show you some data soon.
p238
aa(lp239
VBut we're about to embark upon an extremely ambitious approach,
p240
aVin which we aim to turn on whole suites of genes
p241
aVthat are already present in every crop.
p242
aVThey're just never turned on under extreme drought conditions.
p243
aVI leave it up to you to decide
p244
aVwhether those should be called GM or not.
