aa(lp290
VNow to the final approach.
p291
aVMy research has shown that there's considerable similarity
p292
aVin the mechanisms of desiccation tolerance in seeds and resurrection plants.
p293
aVSo I ask the question,
p294
aVare they using the same genes?
p295
aVOr slightly differently phrased,
p296
aVare resurrection plants using genes evolved in seed desiccation tolerance
p297
aVin their roots and leaves?
p298
aVHave they retasked these seed genes
p299
aVin roots and leaves of resurrection plants?
p300
aa(lp301
VAnd I answer that question,
p302
aVas a consequence of a lot of research from my group
p303
aVand recent collaborations from a group of Henk Hilhorst in the Netherlands,
p304
aVMel Oliver in the United States
p305
aVand Julia Buitink in France.
p306
aVThe answer is yes,
p307
aVthat there is a core set of genes that are involved in both.
p308
aa(lp309
VAnd I'm going to illustrate this very crudely for maize,
p310
aVwhere the chromosomes below the off switch
p311
aVrepresent all the genes that are required for desiccation tolerance.
p312
aVSo as maize seeds dried out at the end of their period of development,
p313
aVthey switch these genes on.
p314
aVResurrection plants switch on the same genes
p315
aVwhen they dry out.
p316
aVAll modern crops, therefore,
p317
aVhave these genes in their roots and leaves,
p318
aVthey just never switch them on.
p319
aVThey only switch them on in seed tissues.
p320
aa(lp321
VSo what we're trying to do right now
p322
aVis to understand the environmental and cellular signals
p323
aVthat switch on these genes in resurrection plants,
p324
aVto mimic the process in crops.
p325
aa(lp326
VAnd just a final thought.
p327
aVWhat we're trying to do very rapidly
p328
aVis to repeat what nature did in the evolution of resurrection plants
p329
aVsome 10 to 40 million years ago.
